},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"c99759",
"children":[
"Hyponatremia"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_np_s5_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a623cc",
"children":[
"The first step in assessing low serum sodium is to determine whether true hyponatremia is present by measuring serum osmolality."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"bbb6d2",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Isotonic hyponatremia"
]
},
" is a laboratory artifact caused by severe hyperlipidemia or hyperproteinemia. In isotonic hyponatremia, the measured osmolality is normal."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"039370",
"children":[
"If ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"true hyponatremia"
]
},
" exists, classify it as hypertonic or hypotonic."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f90e67",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Hypertonic hyponatremia"
]
},
" (osmolality >295 mOsm/kg H",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
"O) is caused by the presence of an osmotically active substance, such as:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"b9fca4",
"children":[
"glucose (most common)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a14f85",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"blood urea nitrogen",
"children":[
"BUN"
]
},
" "
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"5b1e3c",
"children":[
"alcohols"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"397d7f",
"children":[
"mannitol"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"3d54ac",
"children":[
"sorbitol"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"e28c2c",
"children":[
"glycine (bladder irrigation during urologic procedures)"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f90d02",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Hypotonic hyponatremia"
]
},
" (osmolality <275 mOsm/kg H",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
"O) is the most common form of hyponatremia and is further classified based on the patient's volume status."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_np_s5_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"faba38",
"children":[
"Causes of ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion",
"children":[
"SIADH"
]
},
" include malignancy (",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"small cell lung cancer",
"children":[
"SCLC"
]
},
"); intracranial pathology; and pulmonary diseases, especially those that increase intrathoracic pressure and decrease venous return to the heart. Many medications can cause SIADH, including thiazides, ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor",
"children":[
"SSRI"
]
},
"s,"
]
},
" tricyclic antidepressants, opioids, phenothiazines, and carbamazepine."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"0760bc",
"children":[
"Do not miss adrenal insufficiency as a cause of hypotonic hyponatremia."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_np_s5_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"92a1eb",
"children":[
"IV volume replacement with normal saline is indicated for hypovolemic hypotonic hyponatremia resulting from ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"volume depletion"
]
},
"."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"98063d",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Acute symptomatic isovolemic hypotonic hyponatremia"
]
},
" (urine osmolality >100 mOsm/kg H",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
"O) should be treated with a 100-mL bolus of 3% saline to increase the serum sodium by 2.0 to 3.0 mEq/L."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"dbc88a",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Chronic symptomatic isovolemic hypotonic hyponatremia"
]
},
" (>48 hours or unknown) should be treated to a target of 4 to 6 mEq/L in 24 hours."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c2f53c",
"children":[
"If neurologic impairment is significant (seizures or coma), sodium can be acutely increased 2.0-4.0 mEq/L using a bolus of 3% saline as long as the total increase remains â‰¤10 mEq/L in 24 hours."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"1488f9",
"children":[
"If the serum sodium concentration is overcorrected, administer desmopressin and IV 5% dextrose in water. ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Central pontine myelinolysis (osmotic demyelination syndrome) may occur if hyponatremia is corrected too rapidly."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"4631a0",
"children":[
"Water restriction is used initially for asymptomatic or minimally symptomatic outpatients with ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"SIADH"
]
},
". Demeclocycline can also be used for outpatients who do not respond to fluid restriction. The IV V",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"1"
]
},
" and V",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
" receptor antagonist conivaptan and the oral V",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
" receptor antagonist tolvaptan (vaptans) are approved for treatment of euvolemic and hypervolemic hyponatremia. Oral tolvaptan should be reserved for the management of a serum sodium concentration <120 mEq/L and persistent SIADH that has failed water restriction. ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"No data show that the vaptans are associated with improved patient outcomes compared with conventional therapy."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"1221f2",
"children":[
"Vaptan agents should not be used to treat hypovolemic hyponatremia or acute symptomatic hyponatremia."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"c75a25",
"children":[
"Unless documentation indicates that hyponatremia is acute, treat all cases of hyponatremia as chronic."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_np_s5_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"8502ae",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 53-year-old man has a 3-week history of increasing weakness and anorexia. On physical examination, his volume status is normal. Laboratory studies: serum creatinine, 0.8 mg/dL; serum sodium, 123 mEq/L; potassium, 3.4 mEq/L; and urine sodium, 110 mEq/L."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c6a5ba",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose SIADH. For management, select serum osmolality measurement to confirm the presence of hypo-osmolality. If hypo-osmolality is present, the patient likely has SIADH (most common), thyroid disease, or adrenal insufficiency."
]
}
]
}
]
